I can't rave enough about this place. As Cuban, raised in Miami, I have very high standards for places that say they sell Cuban food. I've tried so-called Cuban places in nearly every major city in the U.S. outside of Florida and am usually disappointed. This place, however, is excellent. Between the appetizers, food, and pastelitos, this place is the most authentic Cuban spot I've been to outside of Florida. Croquetas? Nailed it. Pastelitos de Guayaba? Nailed it. Nobody has those outside Miami! (Maybe one place in Manhattan, NYC).  Bottom line: if you're in Chicago and want real Cuban food, not American food masquerading as Cuban food, hit this place up. I'll be back next time I'm in town.

Bad experience, had only a few employees making wait times super long. It was like they only had 1 cook and stove. The owner Robert was dressed in jeans and was very rude. We explained to Robert we had been waiting a very long time for our take out order, over an hour, he exclaimed with a sore attitude he was very busy; he proclaimed that excuse many times. After a few more attempts to find out why it was taking so long to get our orders, Robert braizingly called me an a$$wipe; WoW! We demanded a refund for our prepaid food at that point and Robert refused; and kept us hostage waiting for food. We saw almost every dine in customer happily recieve food while we were waiting, not to mention there were at least 4 drivers like Grubhub waiting as long for their food; those poor drivers were also treated similarly by Robert. Stay away from this place, Cuba probably treats their prisoners better than this joint treats their customers.

Went for a late lunch with husband, son and his wife yesterday.  Easy to find parking. Greeted promptly and with a smile.  Allowed to pick a table.  Pan con ajo basket was warm and tasty.  We had a second one.  Beer was cold.  We chose mariquitas con mojo as our appetizer. Also tasty.  Nice presentation.  Mojitos were so good we had two each.  For entrees we chose tilapia criolla, lechón asado, y rabo encendido.  Side dishes ranged from yuca, congrí, arroz blanco y habichuelas negras.  We all shared because it was all sabroso!  For dessert we had flan and tres leches.  Not disappointed.  Liked the ambiance and service.  Spent over two hours there and went fast.  Highly recommended.  Authentic, tasty, friendly staff. You will come back.
